[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is stable at 212. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 47 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
The Americas region reported 45 674 new cases (53.4 % of the global newly reported cases) and 2453 deaths (49.2% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 71.0% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 12.1% and Canada at 3.1%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 41.6% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 27.8%, Canada at 10.8%, Mexico at 7.3%, and Chile at 3.6%. Note that Ecuador did not report any cases, probably related to weekend reporting.

The European region reported 29 659 new cases (34.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 2307 deaths (46.3% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 42.3% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 15.0%, Turkey 7.9%, and Italy 7.8%. Note that Spain did not report any newly confirmed cases, probably a function of weekend reporting.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5347 new cases (6.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 104 deaths (2.1% of the global newly reported deaths). Saudi Arabia reported 1223 new cases representing 22.9% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran at 21.6%, Qatar 17.4%, Pakistan at 11.3%, and the United Arab Emirates at 10.0%. This is the 3rd consecutive day that Saudi Arabia surpassed Iran.

The African region reported 1154 new cases (1.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 26 deaths (0.52% of the global newly reported deaths). Ghana reported 23.5% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by South Africa at 16.0%, Algeria at 10.9%, Cameroon at 8.9%, Guinea at 8.5%, and Nigeria at 7.9%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1482 new cases (1.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 15 deaths (0.30% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 62.8% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 19.2%, and Japan at 13.7%. Given the high proportion of cases reported by Singapore, removing Singapore from the denominator, the Philippines represents 51.7% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan at 36.8% and Malaysia at 6.9%.

The South East Asia region reported 2214 new cases (2.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 77 deaths (1.5% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 63.1% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 18.9% and Indonesia at 12.4%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 51.1% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 33.6%, Sri Lanka 7.7%, and the Maldives 6.2%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region through (27 Apr 2020) at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend; the European region appears to have its cyclical weekend drop. The America's region does not appear to have decreased even though there were 29 countries reporting no new cases in the past 24 hours. One sees a gradual increase in the number of cases from the Africa Region.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
